03858nam a22006735i 9780814759196DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147591967 a10.18574/97808147591962doi  a(DE-B1597)547707  a(OCoLC)779828464  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS508.A8bN56 2016 7aLIT0040302bisacsh04a810.9352542231 aNinh, erin Khuê, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIngratitude :bThe Debt-Bound Daughter in Asian American Literature /cerin Khuê Ninh. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Filial Debtor: Jade Snow Wong -- t2. Refractions of Harm: Maxine Hong Kingston -- t3. The Caring of Jailers: Evelyn Lau, Catherine Liu -- t4. Desirable Daughters: Fae Myenne Ng, Elaine Mar, Chitra Divakaruni -- tAfterword: The Ending -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnger and bitterness tend to pervade narratives written by second generation Asian American daughters, despite their largely unremarkable upbringings. In Ingratitude, erin Khuê Ninh explores this apparent paradox, locating in the origins of these women's maddeningly immaterial suffering not only racial hegemonies but also the structure of the immigrant family itself. She argues that the filial debt of these women both demands and defies repayment-all the better to produce the docile subjects of a model minority.Through readings of Jade Snow Wong's Fifth Chinese Daughter, Maxine Hong Kingston's The Woman Warrior, Evelyn Lau's Runaway: Diary of a Street Kid, Catherine Liu's Oriental Girls Desire Romance, and other texts, Ninh offers not an empirical study of intergenerational conflict so much as an explication of the subjection and psyche of the Asian American daughter. She connects common literary tropes to their theoretical underpinnings in power, profit, and subjection. In so doing, literary criticism crosses over into a kind of collective memoir of the Asian immigrants' daughter as an analysis not of the daughter, but for and by her.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexAsian American authors. 0aFathers and daughters. 0aMothers and daughters. 0aObedience. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Asian American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814759196.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK